"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035031","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-14","<p>The controller at each privately managed prison has regular review meetings with the contractor against a range of performance indicators that will reflect numbers of staff in post, recruitment, training, sickness, and attrition. Any concerns in relation to these performance indicators, including concerns about staffing levels to delivery an appropriate standard, are discussed at these meetings. Where action is needed, progress is monitored by the Controller and escalated within HMPPS where appropriate action can be taken in accordance with the contract. Controllers submit contractual performance information monthly on the contract that the provider operates. Controllers report to a Senior Contract Manager and are supported by Commercial Contract Managers.</p><p> </p><p>As we have previously stated all staffing matters, including the responsibility for ensuring the availability of sufficiently trained and experienced staff to maintain safe and decent prisons, lies with Contractors. There is no requirement in the contracts to agree staffing levels with the Ministry of Justice and as a consequence the controller is not responsible for staffing levels in the contract that the provider operates.</p><p> </p><p>Private providers continue to play an important role in the prison estate and I can assure you that performance of all providers is closely monitored and we will not hesitate to take action where standards fall short.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","205275 ; 205276","2019-01-14T17:38:32.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035031/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035031/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-04","Prisons: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how often HMPPS Controllers are required to submit written updates on their establishments.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","205274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035032","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-14","<p>The controller at each privately managed prison has regular review meetings with the contractor against a range of performance indicators that will reflect numbers of staff in post, recruitment, training, sickness, and attrition. Any concerns in relation to these performance indicators, including concerns about staffing levels to delivery an appropriate standard, are discussed at these meetings. Where action is needed, progress is monitored by the Controller and escalated within HMPPS where appropriate action can be taken in accordance with the contract. Controllers submit contractual performance information monthly on the contract that the provider operates. Controllers report to a Senior Contract Manager and are supported by Commercial Contract Managers.</p><p> </p><p>As we have previously stated all staffing matters, including the responsibility for ensuring the availability of sufficiently trained and experienced staff to maintain safe and decent prisons, lies with Contractors. There is no requirement in the contracts to agree staffing levels with the Ministry of Justice and as a consequence the controller is not responsible for staffing levels in the contract that the provider operates.</p><p> </p><p>Private providers continue to play an important role in the prison estate and I can assure you that performance of all providers is closely monitored and we will not hesitate to take action where standards fall short.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","205274 ; 205276","2019-01-14T17:38:32.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035032/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035032/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-04","Prisons: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what reports HMPPS Controllers are required to submit regarding staffing levels at their establishments.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","205275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035033","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-14","<p>The controller at each privately managed prison has regular review meetings with the contractor against a range of performance indicators that will reflect numbers of staff in post, recruitment, training, sickness, and attrition. Any concerns in relation to these performance indicators, including concerns about staffing levels to delivery an appropriate standard, are discussed at these meetings. Where action is needed, progress is monitored by the Controller and escalated within HMPPS where appropriate action can be taken in accordance with the contract. Controllers submit contractual performance information monthly on the contract that the provider operates. Controllers report to a Senior Contract Manager and are supported by Commercial Contract Managers.</p><p> </p><p>As we have previously stated all staffing matters, including the responsibility for ensuring the availability of sufficiently trained and experienced staff to maintain safe and decent prisons, lies with Contractors. There is no requirement in the contracts to agree staffing levels with the Ministry of Justice and as a consequence the controller is not responsible for staffing levels in the contract that the provider operates.</p><p> </p><p>Private providers continue to play an important role in the prison estate and I can assure you that performance of all providers is closely monitored and we will not hesitate to take action where standards fall short.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","205274 ; 205275","2019-01-14T17:38:32.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035033/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035033/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-04","Prisons: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, , what processes are in place to enable HMPPS Controllers to report concerns over staffing levels at their establishments.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","205276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035034","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-01-10","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave him on 16 October 2018 to Question <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2018-10-08/175844/" target="_blank">175844</a>.</p><p>The register of overseas entities will be the first of its kind in the world and we must ensure that we get our legislative proposals right in order to deliver the policy in a full and effective way. The timetable set out in the Written Ministerial Statement [<a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2018-01-24/HCWS425/" target="_blank">HCWS425</a>] referred to in my previous response enables this.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-01-10T16:00:05.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035034/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035034/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-01-04","Property: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2018 to Question 175844 on Property: Ownership, for what reason the Government did not follow the May 2016-April 2018 timeline referred to in the Open Government National Action Plan 2016-18 for bringing forward legislative proposals on the property ownership register.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035035","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>From the information held by HMT on our financial system we have identified 9 non-payroll staff members, as at 31<sup>st</sup> December 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The data for HMRC as at 30 November 2018, identifies 339 non pay-roll staff.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-14T10:36:00.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035035/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035035/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many non-payroll staff are employed in (a) his Department and (b) HMRC.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035036","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>The total spent on non-permanent staff during the financial year 2017/18 was £2,370,569 for HM Treasury. These staff were predominantly non-payroll and mainly related to staff seconded in from other public bodies, but also include short term contract, agency and temporary staff.</p><p> </p><p>In the financial year 2017/18 HMRC spent £18,382,007 on non-payroll staff. This includes interim managers, specialist contractors, clerical and admin staff.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-14T14:57:48.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035036/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035036/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of non-payroll staff employed by (a) his Department and (b) HMRC.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035037","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","205082","2019-01-14T10:47:04.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035037/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035037/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the number of hours worked by non-payroll staff employed by (a) his Department and (b) HMRC.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035038","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","205081","2019-01-14T10:47:04.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035038/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035038/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the gender balance of non-payroll staff employed by (a) his Department and (b) HMRC.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035039","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>Due to the difference in work requirements the Treasury does not make a comparison between payroll and non-payroll staff to give a meaningful average.</p><p> </p><p>In HMRC when we have a temporary requirement or do not have the necessary skills internally, we engage non-payroll staff. We do not make the comparison between payroll and non-payroll staff due to the nature of our requirements for specialist skills, capacity or capability as there is no equivalence on which to give a meaningful average.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-14T10:58:05.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035039/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035039/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the differences in average pay between payroll and non-payroll staff employed in (a) the Treasury and (b) HMRC.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035040","Treasury","false","2019-01-11","<p>The current employees at The Royal Mint are:</p><p>(a) (i) Payroll number of staff of 785</p><p>(ii) Payroll full-time equivalent staff of 763</p><p> </p><p>(b) (i) Non-payroll (agency) number of staff of 237</p><p>(ii) Non-payroll (agency) full-time equivalent staff of 237</p><p> </p><p>The Mint is a publicly-owned company and its staff costs are funded out of its own revenues. The most recent forecasts of staff costs including associated tax and pensions costs for the year ending 31 March 2019 are:</p><p> </p><ol><li><p>Payroll costs of £36.7million</p></li><li><p>Non-payroll (agency) costs of £4.5million.</p></li></ol>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","205091","2019-01-11T10:17:49.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035040/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035040/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Royal Mint: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in the Royal Mint.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035041","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>HMRC’s Wealthy team (a merger of the previous High Net Worth Unit and Affluent teams) as of 31/03/18 had approximately 1137 staff or 1046 full time equivalent staff employed in payroll roles. There were no staff in non-payroll roles. The estimated cost of payroll staff is £40.6m for 2018/19.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","205086","2019-01-14T14:59:51.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035041/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035041/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","High Net Worth Unit: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll roles in HMRC's High Net Worth Unit.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035042","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-14","<p>Public Health England (PHE) is working closely with the charity, Jo’s Cervical Cancer Trust, who lead on Cervical Cancer Prevention Week, and we will be supporting them by our own social media activity. The Department will be supporting PHE’s activity.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England plans to support Cervical Cancer Prevention Week this year with proactive social media activity, including support for Jo’s Trust’s #SmearforSmear campaign to help reinforce the importance of women attending their regular check-ups.</p><p> </p><p>In March 2019, PHE will launch a national campaign to highlight the risks of cervical cancer to encourage women to attend their cervical screening appointment.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-01-14T16:22:40.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035042/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035042/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-04","Cervical Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans his Department has to support Cervical Cancer Prevention Week 2019.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","205221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035043","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>HMRC’s Wealthy team (a merger of the previous High Net Worth Unit and Affluent teams) as of 31/03/18 had approximately 1137 staff or 1046 full time equivalent staff employed in payroll roles. There were no staff in non-payroll roles. The estimated cost of payroll staff is £40.6m for 2018/19.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","205085","2019-01-14T14:59:51.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035043/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035043/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","High Net Worth Unit: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in HMRC's High Net Worth Unit.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035044","Department for Education","false","2019-01-09","<p>The current Sex and Relationship Education guidance, published in 2000, and the draft guidance for the new subjects of relationships education, relationships and sex education, and health education include teaching about sexual and reproductive health and wellbeing. The new guidance, which will be mandatory from September 2020, also covers how different sexually transmitted infections (STIs) are transmitted and key facts about prevention and treatment. Teachers are free to use teaching in this area of the curriculum as an opportunity to inform pupils about the human papilloma virus (HPV) vaccination.</p><p> </p><p>Schools may also teach about cancer awareness, including HPV, in other areas of the curriculum. For example, the secondary science national curriculum and GCSEs include content about STIs and non-communicable diseases, such as cancer.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-01-09T17:45:39.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035044/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035044/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-01-04","Sex and Relationship Education: Human Papillomavirus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will include learning about the HPV vaccination in the new sex education curriculum.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","205222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035045","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>NS&amp;I publishes the average number of full time equivalent staff in its Annual Report and Accounts. During 2017/18, the most recently reported period, on average NS&amp;I employed 188 full time equivalent permanent staff and 4 full time equivalent non-payroll staff.</p><p> </p><p>In this period, on average NS&amp;I employed 191 permanent staff and 4 non-payroll staff.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-01-14T14:37:51.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035045/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035045/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","National Savings and Investments: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll roles in National Savings and Investments.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035046","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>NS&amp;I publishes its staff costs in its Annual Report and Accounts. In 2017/18, the most recent reported period, the cost of NS&amp;I’s payroll staff was £12,987,000, and the cost of non-payroll staff was £456,000.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-01-14T13:59:11.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035046/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035046/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","National Savings and Investments: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in National Savings and Investments.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035047","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>At the end November 2018 the headcount for staff in the Office for Budget Responsibility was 31 and the Full-time equivalent 30.08 FTE. There were no non-payroll roles.</p><p> </p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-14T14:31:24.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035047/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035047/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Office for Budget Responsibility: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll roles in the Office for Budget Responsibility.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035048","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>The last audited value of payroll costs for the Office for Budget Responsibility for the year 2017/2018 was £2,009,000, and there were no non-payroll salary costs. This information can be found in the Annual report and accounts 2017/18. <a href="https://obr.uk/docs/dlm_uploads/ARA2017-18web_version.pdf" target="_blank">https://obr.uk/docs/dlm_uploads/ARA2017-18web_version.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-14T14:27:38.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035048/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035048/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Office for Budget Responsibility: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in the Office for Budget Responsibility.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035049","Treasury","false","2019-01-11","<p>The current employees at The Royal Mint are:</p><p>(a) (i) Payroll number of staff of 785</p><p>(ii) Payroll full-time equivalent staff of 763</p><p> </p><p>(b) (i) Non-payroll (agency) number of staff of 237</p><p>(ii) Non-payroll (agency) full-time equivalent staff of 237</p><p> </p><p>The Mint is a publicly-owned company and its staff costs are funded out of its own revenues. The most recent forecasts of staff costs including associated tax and pensions costs for the year ending 31 March 2019 are:</p><p> </p><ol><li><p>Payroll costs of £36.7million</p></li><li><p>Non-payroll (agency) costs of £4.5million.</p></li></ol>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","205084","2019-01-11T10:17:48.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035049/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035049/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Royal Mint: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll roles in the Royal Mint.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035050","Treasury","false","2019-01-11","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer’s private office cost for payroll staff between April and November 2018 was £461,020.</p><p> </p><p>There was no cost for non-payroll staff.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-11T10:14:38.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035050/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035050/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in his private office.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035051","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>(a) The total number of staff at the Debt Management Office as at March 2018 were (i) 118 payroll roles and (ii) 16 non-payroll roles.</p><p> </p><p>(b) The total full-time equivalent staff at the Debt Management Office for the financial year 2017-18 were (i) 110 payroll roles and (ii) 12 non-payroll roles.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-14T10:55:09.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035051/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035051/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","UK Debt Management Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll roles in the Debt Management Office.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035052","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>The cost of staff in the Debt Management Office for the financial year 2017-18 were (a) £8,894,000 for payroll staff and (b) £2,121,000 for non-payroll staff.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-14T10:46:13.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035052/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035052/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","UK Debt Management Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in the Debt Management Office.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035053","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<ol><li><p>The average number of Full Time Equivalent (FTE) staff on payroll between 2017 and 2018 in the Valuation Office Agency (VOA) was 3,337. The average number of FTE staff off-payroll in the VOA in 2017-18 was 43. The total of 3,380 matches the figure published in the Annual Report and Accounts.</p></li><li><p>The average number of staff on payroll between 2017 and 2018 in the VOA was 3,575 and the average number of staff off - payroll in the VOA between 2017 and 2018 was 47.</p></li></ol>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-01-14T14:39:07.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035053/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035053/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Valuation Office Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll roles in the Valuation Office Agency.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035054","Treasury","false","2019-01-09","<p>As of 31 December 2018, the Financial Conduct Authority has 3,936 payroll staff (3,804 full-time equivalent) and 239 non-payroll staff (234 full-time equivalent). The FCA is funded through a levy on the financial services industry.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","205098","2019-01-09T14:49:18.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035054/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035054/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Financial Conduct Authority: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll roles in the Financial Conduct Authority.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035055","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>The cost to the public purse of payroll staff for 2017 to 2018 was £138,258,788 and non-payroll staff was £2,917,225. The total of £141,176,013 matches the figure published in the annual report and accounts which can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/valuation-office-agency-annual-report-and-accounts-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">Valuation Office Agency annual report and accounts 2017 to 2018 - GOV.UK</a></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-01-14T13:52:24.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035055/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035055/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Valuation Office Agency: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in the Valuation Office Agency.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035056","Treasury","false","2019-01-09","<p>As of 31 December 2018, the Financial Conduct Authority has 3,936 payroll staff (3,804 full-time equivalent) and 239 non-payroll staff (234 full-time equivalent). The FCA is funded through a levy on the financial services industry.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","205096","2019-01-09T14:49:18.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035056/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035056/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Financial Conduct Authority: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in the Financial Conduct Authority.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035057","Treasury","false","2019-01-09","<p>As stated in the Office of Tax Simplification Annual Report, during the year to 31 March 2018, a total of 20 people worked for the OTS at some stage, either full-time or part-time. Across the year as a whole this amounted to the equivalent of 8.25 full time people.</p><p> </p><p>These staff were all payroll.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-01-09T15:53:02.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035057/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035057/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Office of Tax Simplification: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (I) payroll and (b) non-payroll roles in the Office of Tax Simplification.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035058","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>The Government published its long-term economic analysis of EU Exit on 28 November 2018: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/exiting-the-european-union-publications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/exiting-the-european-union-publications</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Tables 4.4 and 4.5 of the publication show the estimated long-term impact on real wages from changes to UK trade under different EU Exit scenarios. Changes to UK trade include different UK-EU trading relationships, and the modelled benefits of assumed new trade deals agreed between the UK and non-EU countries, assuming no other changes.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-01-14T10:39:11.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035058/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035058/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the potential effect of the EU withdrawal agreement on wage levels.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035059","Treasury","false","2019-01-09","<p>As stated in the Office of Tax Simplification (OTS) 2017/18 Annual Report, the OTS’s budget for the year April 2017 to March 2018 was £870,000, of which the pay element was £680,000.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-01-09T15:54:07.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035059/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035059/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Office of Tax Simplification: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of (a) payroll and (b) non-payroll staff in the Office of Tax Simplification.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035060","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>The Government published its long-term economic analysis of EU Exit on 28 November 2018. The publication sets out the impact of different EU exit scenarios on Public Sector Net Borrowing (PSNB), which is a UK-wide metric.</p><p>The publication also contains an assessment of the economic impact of EU exit on different sectors. For example, the analysis shows that manufacturing sectors are estimated to have significantly higher output in the White Paper scenario than under no deal.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-01-14T10:19:08.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035060/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035060/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the potential fiscal effect of the EU Withdrawal Agreement on the manufacturing sector.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035061","Treasury","false","2019-01-09","<p>As at the 30<sup>th</sup> November 2018 in the Chancellor’s Office there were 10 paid staff with a full time equivalent of 10 FTE. No non-payroll roles.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-09T16:47:45.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035061/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035061/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) staff and (b) full-time equivalent staff are employed in (i) payroll and (ii) non-payroll roles in his private office.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035062","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>On 28 November the Bank of England published analysis on how the short-term impact of leaving the EU could affect the Bank’s ability to meet its objectives for monetary and financial stability. This analysis was produced by the Bank of England for the Treasury Committee and Parliament, and it was rightly produced and presented by the Bank independently of Government.</p><p> </p><p>In line with the practice of successive administrations, the details of ministerial discussions are not normally discussed.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-01-14T11:10:19.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035062/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035062/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union on the Bank of England's forecasts for the economy after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035063","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>Investment is crucial for the economic future of this country, and the government is committed to ensuring that businesses and infrastructure projects have access to the finance they need.</p><p>As the Chancellor has made clear we are actively exploring options for a future relationship with the European Investment Bank Group and these discussions will take place as part of the wider future relationship negotiations. However, as the Chancellor said in his 2017 Mansion House speech, if we do not maintain a relationship with the EIB group, we will be prepared.</p><p>The government has a range of existing tools to support investment, including the £40bn UK Guarantees Scheme, and the British Business Bank. As announced at the Budget 2018, the government is reviewing how it supports infrastructure finance to ensure good projects continue to be able to raise the finance they need. Additionally, if no future relationship with the EIB Group is in place when the UK leaves the EU, the government will provide the British Business Bank with the resources to enable it to make up to £200m additional investment in venture capital and growth finance in 2019/20. The government will keep the support for financing infrastructure and high-growth businesses under review as negotiations progress.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-01-14T10:21:37.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035063/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035063/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","European Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on access to investment funds of Government proposals to withdraw from the European Investment Bank.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035064","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>The government agreed the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS)-funded Alternative Remedies Package (the Package) with the European Commission (EC) in September 2017 as a resolution to RBS’ final State aid commitment to divest the part of its business known as Williams &amp; Glyn. The Package was agreed on the basis that it is capable of having an equivalent positive impact on competition in the UK business banking market as the original State aid commitment.</p><p> </p><p>Banking Competition Remedies Ltd (BCR) was established in 2018 as the independent body to implement and oversee the Package. HM Treasury has appointed an independent third-party monitor which reports regularly to HM Treasury on the performance of BCR. The Package consists of a £425m Capability and Innovation Fund (CIF) and a £350m Incentivised Switching Scheme (ISS).</p><p> </p><p>The CIF comprises of 15 pre-determined grants divided into four pools, each with a distinct pro-competition purpose based on criteria agreed between HM Treasury and the EC. Eligible challenger banks and other financial services providers can compete for these grants to develop and improve their financial products and services available to SMEs, and to improve their capability to compete with RBS in the provision of banking services to SMEs.</p><p> </p><p>BCR has responsibility for communicating information regarding the Package to the market. Further information on the Package, including eligibility criteria and timelines for implementation is available on BCR’s website: https://bcr-ltd.com/</p><p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","205205 ; 205206 ; 205207 ; 205208 ; 205209","2019-01-14T10:29:30.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035064/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035064/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Royal Bank of Scotland: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure that grant funding from the RBS alternative remedies package is not used to update legacy bank IT infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","205204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035065","Treasury","false","2019-01-14","<p>Both departments use contingent labour to quickly deploy specialist expertise, drive change and deliver increased efficiency to cover periods of increased levels of workforce demand. These individuals provide skills including (but not limited to) legal, administration, commercial, facilities management, finance and digital services.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2019-01-14T10:53:42.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035065/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1035065/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-01-04","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what services non-payroll staff provide to (a) the Treasury and (b) HMRC.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","205106"
